SIMPLE: oversee
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Oversee
<hw>O`ver*see"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Oversaw</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Overseen</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Overseeing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>ofers⟦eacute⟧on</ets> to survey, to despise. See <er>Over</er>, and
<er>See</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To superintend; to watch over; to direct; to look or
see after; to overlook{2}.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To omit or neglect seeing; to overlook{5}.</def>
<mark>[archaic]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To see unintentionally or unexpectedly; -- the
visual analogy to <er>overhear</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oversee</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Oversee
<hw>O`ver*see"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To see too or too much;
hence, to be deceived.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The most expert gamesters may sometimes <qex>oversee</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your partiality to me is much <qex>overseen</qex>, if you think me
fit to correct your Latin.</q> <rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overseer</ent>⟦br⟧
